04537nam a22005295i 9780773582422DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735824227 a10.1515/97807735824222doi  a(DE-B1597)655338  a(OCoLC)867557381  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1528b.H46 2016eb 7aHIS0070002bisacsh04a861.642231 aHenighan, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSandino's Nation :bErnesto Cardenal and Sergio Ramírez Writing Nicaragua, 1940-2012 /cStephen Henighan. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tCitation System -- tPriest and Politician as Arbiters of Sandino’s Nation -- tNicaraguan History to 1979 -- tCardenal: The Contemplative’s Poetry (1940–68) -- tRamírez: From Student Activist to Exiled Writer (1956–75) -- tCardenal: The First Incursion into Prose (1970–75) -- tNicaraguan History, 1979–90 -- tRamírez: Towards the Novelist as Vice-President (1976–89) -- tCardenal: The Revolutionary Poet (1969–89) -- tNicaraguan History after 1990 -- tRamírez: The Politician as Writer after the Revolution (1990–2006) -- tCardenal: The Poet as Memoirist, the Nation as Relic (1990–2006) -- tOrtega’s Nation: Two Dissident Writers Face Globalization (2007–12) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aErnesto Cardenal and Sergio Ramírez are two of the most influential Latin American intellectuals of the late twentieth and early twenty-first centuries. Addressing Nicaragua's struggle for self-definition from divergent ethnic, religious, generational, political, and class backgrounds, they constructed distinct yet compatible visions of national history, anchored in a reappraisal of the early twentieth-century insurgent leader Augusto César Sandino. During the Sandinista Revolution of 1979-90, Cardenal, appointed Nicaragua's minister of culture, became one of the most provocative and internationally recognized figures of liberation theology, while Ramírez, a member of the revolutionary junta, and later elected vice-president of Nicaragua, emerged as an authoritative figure for third world nationalism. But before all else, the two were groundbreaking creative writers. Through a close reading of the works by Nicaragua's best-known and most prolific modern authors, Sandino's Nation studies the construction of Nicaraguan national identity during three distinct periods of the country’s recent history - before, during, and after the 1979-90 revolution. Stephen Henighan offers rigorous textual analyses of poems, memoirs, essays, and novels, interwoven with a sharply narrated history of Nicaragua. The only comprehensive study of the careers of Cardenal and Ramírez, Sandino's Nation is essential to understanding transformations to both Nicaragua and the role of the writer in Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Nicaraguany20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezNicaragua. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Central America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358242240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773582422423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773582422/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles